comments.body:
>Is there a way to distinguish between code actions that are explicitly requested by the users and code action requests that are automatically triggered by the editor?

Unfortunately not. On cursor move VS Code sends a code actions request with `only = null`, i.e. it requests all possible actions. Then if the user explicitly requests "Refactor..." or "Quick Fix...", it reuses the info it has already retrieved. I don't think it ever sends a code actions request in which it specifies a value for `only`.

I'm not sure how much work it would be, but as a long term solution would it make sense for `Compilers` (or some layer on top of that) to cache the typechecking results? It could be computed once per `didChange` and then reused by various code actions, or whoever else might need it.

@olafurpg What if we reverted to the previous implementation, using `definitionProvider` and `symbolSearch` instead of the presentation compiler? The code was more cumbersome, but would that alleviate your performance concerns? It was traversing a pre-built scalameta tree, then looking up the symbol in semanticdb, and finally looking up the symbol's definition in the mtags index, all of which should be faster than typechecking?

@gabro That sounds reasonable but IIUC, even if we made the API nicer, any implementation that uses the presentation compiler hits the problem of triggering an expensive typecheck every time we generate the code action.

Not quite sure how to proceed from here...

@gabro suggested a nice solution in an offline conversation that the code action only needs to analyze whether the refactoring can be applied at the given position. If the refactoring is eligible, we return an ID for a command thatÂ performs the expensive analysis only if user explicitly chooses to apply the code action.

I have a feeling it will be best add one method to the `PresentationCompiler` API that returns what code actions are available at a given position. This method will need to be aware of all available code actions. For "add named argument", this analysis involves checking only if the cursor is above an argument to a method call.

What do you think?
